The Debt Management Office (DMO) has said it plans to raise between N420 billion and N510 billion through Federal Government of Nigeria, FGN Bonds between January and March this year. The debt office in its bond issuance calender for the first quarter of the year said it plans to raise the funds from reopening of previous bonds. According to the calendar, between N135 billion and N165 billion is expected to be raised from the reopening of the 12.75 per cent FGN APR 2023 five year bond within three months. Also, it plans to raise between N135 billion and N165 billion through the reopening of the 14.55 per cent FGN APR  2029 10 year bond, while it is set to raise between N150 billion and N180 billion through the 14.8 per cent FGN APR 2049, 20 year bond. The bonds issuance are planned for January 22nd, February 19th and March 25th of this year. In the 12 months of 2019, the government through the DMO had raised N1.249 trillion through the FGN Bonds that was raised every month while N5.762 billion had been raised though the FGN Savings Bond which is also raised on a monthly basis. The amount raised from the FGN Bonds was more than the N1.19 trillion which it had set out to raise in the course of the year as interest in the bond market increased on impressive yields and improve foreign exchange conditions. Meanwhile, the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) has shifted forward the date for the first meeting of the Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) which was earlier slated for next week. A release issued on Monday night by the apex bank and signed by the Director, Corporate Communications reads, “the first meeting of the Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) of the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) for 2020, earlier slated to hold on Monday and Tuesday, January 20 and 21, 2020, respectively, has now been rescheduled for Thursday and Friday, January 23 and 24, 2020. “The CBN regrets any inconvenience this change may have caused its stakeholders and the general public,” concluded the statement.